20 SECTION 9. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 396.34 of Title 59, unless there
22 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. No person shall dispose of the body of any deceased person
24 by natural organic reduction or other similar means, within this
Req. No. 16643 Page 17

1 stat e, without first having obtained from the Oklahoma Funeral Board
2 an annual license to operate a natural organic reduction facility.
3 B. Application for an annual license shall be made to the
4 Executive Director of the Board upon forms prescribed and furnished
5 by the Executive Director, shall give the location of the natural
6 organic reduction facility, and any other information as the
7 Executive Director shall require, and shall be accompanied by the
8 natural organic reduction facility license fee pursuant to Section
9 396.4 of this title. A natural organic reduction facility shall not
10 be licensed separately from a funeral or commercial embalming
11 establishment but shall be licensed in conjunction with and operated
12 by a funeral service or commercial embalming establishment. Annual
13 licenses shall expire on December 31 each year, shall specify the
14 name or names of the owners of the crematory and the location
15 thereof, the funeral director in charge, and shall not be
16 transferable either as to the ownership of the natural organic
17 reduction facility, the funeral director in charge or as to the
18 location thereof. The first annual license issued for any natural
19 organic reduction facility at any location shall not be issued by
20 the Executive Director until the executive director has been
21 satisfied.
22 C. All funeral establishments performing natural organic
23 reduction facility shall have a licensed funeral director in charge.
24
Req. No. 16643 Page 18

1 D. Each funeral establishment performing reduction services
2 shall keep records as required by the Board to assure compliance
3 with all laws relating to the disposition of dead human remains and
4 shall file annually with the Board a report in the form prescribed
5 by the Board describing the operations of the licensee, including
6 the number of reductions performed, the disposition thereof, and any
7 other information that the Board may require by rule.
8 E. A funeral establishment performing reduction services shall
9 be subject to all local, state, and federal health and environmental
10 requirements and shall obtain all necessary licenses and permits
11 from the Oklahoma Funeral Board, and the appropriate federal and
12 state health and environmental authorities.
13 F. All natural organic reduction facilities shall be subject to
14 inspection, at all reasonable times, by the Board or its duly
15 authorized agents or employees.
16 G. License Required. A dead human body may only undergo
17 natural organic reduction in the State of Oklahoma at a natural
18 organic reduction facility licensed by the Oklahoma Funeral Board.
19 H. General Requirements. Any building to be used as a natural
20 organic reduction facility must comply with all applicable local and
21 state building codes, zoning laws, and ordinances and environmental
22 standards. A natural organic reduction facility must have on site:
23 1. A natural organic reduction system capable of reducing human
24 remains through natural organic reduction, which includes:
Req. No. 16643 Page 19

1 a. an identification system that maintains a secure chain
2 of custody and prevents commingling throughout the
3 process,
4 b. a vessel that can reach a minimum one hundred thirty-
5 one degrees (131°) Fahrenheit temperature for seventy-
6 two (72) consecutive hours to destroy pathogens,
7 c. a vessel monitoring system to ensure those temperature
8 thresholds are met;
9 2. A motorized mechanical device for processing the remains in
10 reduction; and
11 3. A refrigerated holding facility for the retention of dead
12 human bodies awaiting natural organic reduction.
13 The holding facility must be secure from access by anyone except
14 the authorized personnel of the natural organic reduction facility,
15 preserve the dignity of the remains, and protect the health and
16 safety of the natural organic reduction facility personnel. The
17 room where human remains are prepared for natural organic reduction
18 must be private and must not have a general passageway through it.
19 All windows or other openings to the outside must be treated in a
20 manner that prevents viewing into the room where the deceased will
21 be prepared for natural organic reduction. A window for authorized
22 family members or their designees is not a violation of this
23 section.
24
Req. No. 16643 Page 20

1 The room must, at all times, be secure from the entrance of
2 unauthorized persons. Authorized persons are:
3 a. licensed funeral directors or natural organic
4 reduction facility operators,
5 b. registered apprentices,
6 c. public officials or representatives in the discharge
7 of their official duties,
8 d. the person or persons with the right to control the
9 disposition of the deceased,
10 e. other individuals authorized by the authorizing agent
11 or if accompanied by an authorized person.
12 I. Any room where the body is prepared for natural organic
13 reduction must be properly lit and ventilated with an exhaust fan.
14 It must be equipped with a functional sink with running hot and cold
15 water. It must have nonporous flooring, such that a sanitary
16 condition is provided. The walls and ceiling must be covered with
17 tile, or by plaster or sheetrock painted with washable paint or
18 other appropriate material, such that a sanitary condition is
19 provided. The doors, walls, ceiling, and windows must be constructed
20 to prevent odors from entering other parts of the building.
21 J. All licensed natural organic reduction facilities shall
22 develop, implement, and maintain an identification procedure whereby
23 dead human bodies can be identified from the time the natural
24 organic reduction facility accepts delivery of the body until the
Req. No. 16643 Page 21

1 redu ced remains are released to an authorized party. After
2 reduction, an identifying disk, tab, or other permanent label shall
3 be placed within the reduced remains container or containers before
4 the remains are released from the natural organic reduction
5 facility. Each identification disk, tab, or label shall have a
6 number that shall be recorded on all paperwork regarding the
7 decedent. This procedure shall be designed to reasonably ensure
8 that the proper body is reduced and that the remains are returned to
9 the appropriate party.
10 K. The natural organic reduction facility must:
11 1. Ensure that the material in the natural organic reduction
12 vessel naturally reaches and maintains a minimum of one hundred
13 thirty-one degrees (131°) Fahrenheit for a minimum of seventy-two
14 (72) consecutive hours during the process of reduction;
15 2. Ensure reduced remains have less than one-hundredth (.01)
16 milligram/kilogram dry weight of any physical contaminants;
17 3. Collect material samples for analysis that are
18 representative of each instance of reduction, using a sample method
19 such as those described in the U.S. Composting Council 2002 Test
20 Methods for the Examination of Composting and Compost, method 02.01-
21 A through E;
22 4. Develop and use a reduction process in which the reduced
23 remains from the process do not exceed the following limits:
24
Req. No. 16643 Page 22

1 a. metal and other testing parameters limit (mg/kg dry
2 weight), unless specified,
3 b. fecal coliform less than one thousand (1,000) most
4 probable number per gram of total solids (dry weight),
5 or
6 c. salmonella less than three (3) most probable number
7 per four (4) grams of total solids (dry weight),
8 d. cadmium less than or equal to seven and one-tenths
9 (7.1) parts per million (ppm)
10 e. lead less than or equal to one hundred fifty (150)
11 ppm,
12 f. mercury less than or equal to five (5) ppm,
13 g. arsenic less than or equal to eleven (11) ppm,
14 h. selenium less than or equal to eighteen (18) ppm;
15 5. Analyze, using a third-party laboratory, the reduction
16 facility’s material samples of reduced remains according to the
17 following schedule:
18 a. the reduction facility must analyze each of the first
19 twenty instances of reduced remains for the parameters
20 in section 4; if any of the first twenty instances of
21 reduced remains yield results exceeding the limits
22 outlined above, the reduction facility must analyze
23 each additional reduced remains until a total of
24 twenty samples, not including those from the reduced
Req. No. 16643 Page 23

1 remains that were reprocessed as required by the above
2 parameters, have yielded results within the limits
3 above on initial testing,
4 b. after twenty material samples of reduced remains have
5 met the limits in the above parameters, the natural
6 reduction facility must analyze at least twenty-five
7 percent (25%) of the reduction facility’s monthly
8 reduced remains are found to meet the limits, not
9 including any samples that required reprocessing to
10 meet those limits, and after eighty material samples
11 of the reduced remains are found to meet the limits in
12 the above parameters the reduction facility must
13 analyze one randomly chose instance of reduced remains
14 each month form the parameters above. If fecal
15 coliform or salmonella in the tested reduced remains
16 exceeds the limit for that substance the reduction
17 facility must analyze subsequent instance of reduced
18 remains for fecal coliform and salmonella until ten
19 total material samples are found to meet the limits in
20 the above parameters on initial testing, demonstrating
21 the reduction process was effectively corrected;
22 6. Comply with any testing requirements established by the
23 Oklahoma Funeral Board for content parameters in addition to those
24 specified;
Req. No. 16643 Page 24

1 7. Not release any reduced remains that exceed the parameters;
2 and
3 8. Prepare, maintain, and provide to the Oklahoma Funeral
4 Board, upon request, a report for each calendar year detailing the
5 reduction facility’s activities during the previous calendar year.
6 The report must include the following information:
7 a. the name and address of the reduction facility,
8 b. the calendar year covered by the report,
9 c. the body intake log of reduced remains,
10 d. the results of any laboratory analyses of reduced
11 remains, and
12 e. any additional information required by the Oklahoma
13 Funeral Board.
14 L. The reduction facility shall provide for the removal and
15 disposition of any accumulated residue from any reduction vessel,
16 mechanical processor, or other equipment used in the reduction.
17 M. Every reduction facility shall create and maintain on its
18 premises or other business location in Oklahoma an accurate record
19 of every reduction provided. The record shall include all of the
20 following information for each reduction:
21 1. The name of the person or funeral establishment delivering
22 the remains for reduction;
23 2. The name of deceased and the identification number assigned
24 to the remains;
Req. No. 16643 Page 25

1 3. The date of delivery;
2 4. The names of the operator of reduction process and
3 mechanical processor operator;
4 5. The times and date that the remains were removed from the
5 reduction vessel;
6 6. The time, date, and manner of release of the reduced
7 remains;
8 7. The name and address of the person who signed the
9 authorization for reduction; and
10 8. All supporting documentation, including any transit or
11 medical examiner’s permit, the authorization for the reduction.
12 All records shall be maintained for a period of five (5)
13 calendar years after the release of the reduced remains. At the end
14 of this period and subject to any other laws requiring retention of
15 records, the reduction facility may destroy the records by any
16 manner that protects the privacy of the individuals identified.
17 SECTION 10. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
